    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "673436afe9d41f3857b184aee43d14feba45609924f8ca0d5f21d3afe729c423",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "It is trivial that the number of prime factors is\\[>\\frac{\\log \\binom{n}{k}}{\\log n},\\]and this inequality becomes (asymptotic) equality if $k>n^{1-o(1)}$."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "1fe919704b3c5d54bab7fe7c0defc917800129fb2c62f9b022d5c975d5f6cc94",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Let $\\epsilon>0$ and $n$ be large depending on $\\epsilon$. Is it true that for all $n^\\epsilon<k\\leq n^{1-\\epsilon}$ the number of distinct prime divisors of $\\binom{n}{k}$ is\\[(1+o(1))k\\sum_{k<p<n}\\frac{1}{p}?\\]Or perhaps even when $k \\geq (\\log n)^c$?"
    }
  },
